	<a name="in_news"></a><h2>Club Penguin in the News </h2>
	<p><br>
        <strong><a href="../parents/downloads/your-igloo-mine.pdf">Your Igloo or Mine?</a></strong> (pdf)<br>
        <span class="sm_txt">Newsweek | Febuary 23, 2007</span><br>
        <br>
Web sites like Club Penguin have introduced social networking to children. Welcome to MySpace in braces.</p>
	<p>&nbsp;</p>
	<p><strong><a href="../parents/downloads/surfins-safe-for-the-small-set.pdf">Surfin's Safe for the Small Set</a></strong> (pdf)<br>
	  <span class="sm_txt">ContraCostaTimes.com | Febuary 21, 2007</span><br>
	  <br>
	  Club Penguin&rsquo;s ad-free, monitored website meets a need for kid-safe spaces   online, and encourages creativity from young users in a virtual community that   combines game play and chat.</p>
	<p>&nbsp;</p>
	<p><strong><a href="../parents/downloads/club-penguin-beckons-preteen-surfers.pdf">Online, Club Penguin Beckons to Preteen Surfers</a></strong> (pdf)<br>
	  <span class="sm_txt">npr.org | 
	    January 19, 2007</span><br>
	  <br>
	  Club Penguin offers safe Internet entry point for preteen, first-time web users   with their interactive site that supports safe chat, playing games and creating   online community.</p>
	<p>&nbsp;</p>
	<p><strong><a href="../parents/downloads/procession-penguins-arrives.pdf">A Procession of Penguins Arrive on Madison Ave.</a></strong> (pdf)<br>
      <span class="sm_txt">nytimes.com | 
                          January 10, 2007</span><br>
                          <br>
Penguins have become an icon of choice in popular culture-from online gaming, movies and advertising. </p>
	<p>&nbsp;</p>
	<p><strong><a href="../parents/downloads/girls-just-want-to-have-fun-on-computers.pdf">Girls just want to have fun - on computers</a></strong> (pdf)<br>
	  <span class="sm_txt">ScrippsNews.com | 
                            January 04, 2007</span><br>
        <br>
	  Club Penguin is attracting more girls to the traditionally boy-dominated   industry. Betsy Hart discovers why it works for her daugters.</p>
	<p>&nbsp;</p>
	<p><strong><a href="../parents/downloads/children-penguins-turn-trio-into-kingpins.pdf">Children and penguins turn trio into kingpins</a></strong> (pdf)<br>
	  <span class="sm_txt">theglobeandmail.com | 
                        November 13, 2006</span><br>
                        <br>
	  One of Canada's leading daily newspapers features Club Penguin as a "virtual playground" for children describing how it got started, where it's going and how its values are shaping the company's directive.</p>
	<p>&nbsp;</p>
	<p><strong><a href="../parents/downloads/homemaking-parenting-on-thin-ice.pdf">Homemaking: Parenting on thin ice</a></strong> (pdf)<br>
            <span class="sm_txt">post-gazette.com |                        November 11, 2006</span><br>
            <br>
	  But you gotta at least hope, don't   you? One of them clued me in that they'd all joined "Club Penguin," an   online virtual world.</p>
	<p>&nbsp;</p>
	<p><strong><a href="../parents/downloads/How-young-is-too-young-for-MySpace.pdf">How young is too young for MySpace?</a></strong> (pdf)<br>
	  <span class="sm_txt">Moneyweb Holdings Limited | 
                        October 19, 2006</span><br>
            <br>
	  The Wall Street Journal reports the growing popularity of Online communities among children, exploring the impact of virtual activities on a child's development and emphasizing the need for parental involvement.</p>
	<p>&nbsp;</p>
	<p><strong><a href="../parents/downloads/MySpace-For-The-Sandlot-Set.pdf">BusinessWeek Online - MySpace For The Sandlot Set</a></strong> (pdf)<br>
            <span class="sm_txt">businessweek.com | October 2, 2006</span><br>
            <br>
	  A BuisnessWeek writer takes a look at the significance of social networking on children's chat based websites, highlighting Club Penguin as a leader in providing a safe environment for fun while Online.</p>
	<p>&nbsp;</p>
